text.tspan: Each of the 32 output channels (called lanes) can be
mapped on one of the 16 input channels (called cross-lanes,
in short clanes). This restriction has the following effects:
1) Only one bit set per column.
2) Maximal 32 nonzero bits in the overall matrix.
3) The matrix can be represented as a list of 32 integers,
The U Block gets its name from the voltage coupling
The lanes concept exists only within the U-C-I interconnect.
The U Block provides a source for constant voltages,
which can be either +1, -1, +0.1, -0.1 or 0. If turned on,
the "constant source" scheme provides these constants only
on the last two clanes. By cleverly masking the incoming
values from the MBlock, both constants and values can be used
either in the left or right side of the UBlock. It is the job
of a compiler to hide this complex fact from the user.
Each lane can be scaled with a constant coefficient in the
analog unit range [-1,+1]. Unused lanes have coefficients 0.
Each of the 32 input channels (lanes) can be summed into
as many of the 16 output channels (called clanes). Summing
happens because of the current representation of analog
Since distributing a current amongst different targets with
different input impedances has no simple mathematical
analogon, applications should consider the configuration
with similar restrictions as the U block, i.e. set only
one bit per column. This results in maximal 32 nonzero bits
in the overall matrix. The matrix can then be represented
as a list of 32 integers, each in range [0..16].
The I block can implement a gain of factor 1 pr 10 once per
lane, applied at the input of the I block.
